INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'be43226c-a902-49e6-9820-8c91fe5e8a8f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Express Error Handling — Global Handlers and Consistent Error Responses$escape$,
  $escape$Express's error-handling middleware is distinguished by its four-parameter signature `(err, req, res, next)`. Any error passed to `next(err)` — or thrown inside an `async` handler wrapped correctly — bypasses regular middleware and lands here. The key discipline is defining a single error handler at the bottom of your middleware stack, after all routes.

Structure every error response the same way: a `status`, a `message`, and optionally a `code` for machine consumption. Avoid leaking stack traces in production — gate on `process.env.NODE_ENV`.

For async route handlers, Express 5 natively catches rejected promises. On Express 4, wrap handlers with a utility like `asyncHandler` or use `express-async-errors` to avoid repeating `.catch(next)` everywhere.

Centralizing error shaping here means your route handlers stay lean — they only need to throw or call `next(err)` with a typed error object. All serialization, logging, and status-code mapping live in one place, making API contracts predictable for every client.$escape$,
  $escape$// errors/handler.js
function errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {
  const status = err.status ?? err.statusCode ?? 500;
  const isProd = process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production';

  res.status(status).json({
    status,
    code: err.code ?? 'INTERNAL_ERROR',
    message: err.message ?? 'Something went wrong',
    ...(isProd ? {} : { stack: err.stack }),
  });
}

// app.js — must be last, after all routes
app.use(errorHandler);$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
