INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '775460d2-1445-492d-a61e-d4f12fab0cc0',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Express ORM Choices — Query Builders, N+1 Traps, and Safe Migrations$escape$,
  $escape$Express doesn't ship with a data layer — you wire it yourself. That choice matters.

Query builders (Knex.js) give you composable SQL without magic. You control every join and index hint. Ideal when you need raw performance or queries that an ORM would mangle into a suboptimal plan.

Full ORMs (Prisma, Sequelize, TypeORM) trade control for ergonomics. Prisma's type-safe client is the modern default for Express + TypeScript setups.

The N+1 trap hits Express route handlers hard: fetch a list, then loop with individual lookups inside Promise.all. You fire N+1 queries for what should be one. Fix it with eager loading — Prisma's `include`, Sequelize's `{ include: [Model] }`, or an explicit Knex join.

For migrations, both paths converge: `knex migrate:latest` or `prisma migrate deploy` run as a pre-start step in your Dockerfile or CI pipeline — never inside the Express process itself. Running migrations on app boot causes race conditions in multi-instance deploys.

Rule of thumb: reach for Prisma when type safety accelerates development; drop to Knex when your queries outgrow what an ORM generates cleanly.$escape$,
  $escape$// ❌ N+1 — fires one extra query per post inside the route handler
app.get('/posts', async (req, res) => {
  const posts = await prisma.post.findMany();
  const withAuthors = await Promise.all(
    posts.map(p => prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id: p.authorId } }))
  );
  res.json(withAuthors);
});

// ✅ Single JOIN via eager load — one round-trip regardless of result size
app.get('/posts', async (req, res) => {
  const posts = await prisma.post.findMany({
    include: { author: { select: { id: true, name: true } } }
  });
  res.json(posts);
});$escape$,
